[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 41 266 new cases (50.0% of the global newly reported cases), and 2675 deaths (62.8%) were recorded for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 64.6% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 16.4%, and Peru at 5.6%. Recognizing that USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, if newly confirmed cases from the USA are excluded, then Brazil reported 46.2% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 15.7%, Mexico at 10.7%, and Chile at 8.2%. Ecuador has shown downward readjustments of the cumulative cases over the past few days.

The European region reported 24 184 new cases (29.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 1277 deaths (30.0%). Russia reported 45.1% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 16.0%, Spain 12.6%, Turkey 4.6%, Germany 3.9%, and Italy 3.1% each.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 8863 new cases (10.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 125 deaths (2.9%). Saudi Arabia reported 22.2% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan at 12.9%, Iran at 19.0%, Qatar at 12.4%, and the United Arab Emirates at 7.7%.

The African region reported 2296 new cases (2.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 34 deaths (0.80%). South Africa reported 27.8% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ghana at 19.0%, Nigeria at 10.5%, Senegal at 7.7%, Algeria at 7.3%, Gabon at 6.1%, and Guinea-Bissau at 5.2%.

The Western Pacific region reported 962 new cases (1.2% of the global newly reported cases) and 34 deaths (0.80%). Singapore reported 50.5% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 30.4%, and Japan at 7.9%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 61.3%, Japan at 16.0%, Malaysia at 14.7%, and South Korea at 5.7%.

The South East Asia region reported 5020 new cases (6.1% of the global newly reported cases) and 116 deaths (2.7%). India reported 71.8% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 20.6% and Indonesia at 4.6%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 73.0% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 16.5%, Nepal at 5.0%, and the Maldives at 4.4%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 12 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has decreased. The Americas is increasing, as is South East Asia.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
